<REFENTRY id="mktemp">
<REFMETA><REFENTRYTITLE>mktemp</REFENTRYTITLE></REFMETA>

<REFNAMEDIV>
<REFNAME>mktemp</REFNAME>

<REFPURPOSE>
make temporary file name (unique)
</REFPURPOSE>

</REFNAMEDIV>

<REFSYNOPSISDIV>
<SYNOPSIS>
mktemp [-q] [-u] template
</SYNOPSIS>
</REFSYNOPSISDIV>

<REFSECT1>
<TITLE>Description</TITLE>
<PARA>
<COMMAND>mktemp</COMMAND> takes the given file name template and 
overwrites a
portion of it to create a file name.  This file name is unique and
suitable for use by the application.
</PARA>
</REFSECT1>


<REFSECT1>
<title>Options</title>
<variablelist>

<varlistentry>
<term>-q</term>
<listitem>
<para>
fails silently if an error occurs.  This is useful if a script does not
want error output to go to standard error.
</para>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry>
<term>-u</term>
<listitem>
<para>
operates in ``unsafe'' mode.  The temp file will be unlinked before
<COMMAND>mktemp</COMMAND> exits.  This is slightly better than 
mktemp(3) but still
introduces a race condition.  Use of this option is not encouraged.
</para>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

</variablelist>
</REFSECT1>

</REFENTRY>
